<TEXT>
<P>
 THE BASS SAXOPHONE by Josef Skvorecky, translated from the Czech (Ecco Press: 
$12; 209 pp.) . The two novellas in this volume are less compelling than the 
author's recollections of playing American jazz in a Czech village, despite the 
condemnations of the Nazis and Soviets. In "Emoke," Skvorecky uses long, 
rolling sentences to etch the bleak passions of the colorless world of the old 
Communist regime. The narrator of "The Bass Saxophone" risks his life to play 
in a nightmarish jazz concert given by a ragtag circus band for the Nazi 
invaders who banned the music as decadent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
