<TEXT>
<P>
 THE NEW PENGUIN DICTIONARY OF QUOTATIONS edited by J. M. & M. J. Cohen 
(Penguin: $14; 726 pp.) This reference volume has been expanded to include more 
citations from 20th-Century figures. Although the editors note, "it is not 
always those who are most read or respected who have left the greatest number 
of sayings in the popular memory" their choices reflect an Anglophile bias: 
Mishima, Genet, Steinbeck and Mann are omitted, while 178 entries are included 
for Alexander Pope. Comments on the human condition ("A single sentence will 
suffice for modern man: he fornicated and read the papers" -- Camus) are 
juxtaposed with H. H. Munro's "The cook was a good cook, as cooks go; and as 
cooks go, she went." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Book Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
