150 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
STYLE: DESIGN; IMPERFECT WORLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Appreciating the imperfect, impermanent or incomplete isn't the way of the 
West. Yet such qualities, known collectively as wabi-sabi , have been 
celebrated by the Japanese for centuries . In his new book, " Wabi-Sabi : For 
Artists, Designers, Poets & Philosophers" (Stone Bridge Press), 
writer-architect-photographer Leonard Koren explores the traditional Japanese 
aesthetic through close-ups of the commonplace. "Things wabi-sabi often appear 
odd, misshapen, awkward or what many people would consider ugly," he writes. 
"They record the sun, wind, rain, heat and cold in a language of discoloration, 
rust, tarnish, stain, warping, shrinking, shriveling and cracking. Their nicks, 
chips, bruises, scars, dents, peeling and other forms of attrition are a 
testament to histories of use and misuse." Wabi-sabi -- a way of looking at the 
world to challenge the eye of the beholder. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA090494-0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 075843 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
September 4, 1994, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Magazine; Page 36; Magazine Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
