<HEADLINE>
<P>
FOUR-STAR FILMS; 'WHITE HEAT' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kevin Thomas 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 This is the fast-moving gangster classic written by Ivan Goff and Ben Roberts 
from a Virginia Kellogg story. Director Raoul Walsh gets away with placing 
migraine-prone mobster James Cagney (pictured) on his mother's lap without a 
trace of self-consciousness; never was an Oedipus complex presented with so 
little fuss. This 1949 Warners production, which co-stars Virginia Mayo 
(pictured) and Edmond O'Brien, is even more famous fo Cagney's ironic tag line: 
"Top of the world, Ma!" (TMC Sunday at 7:30 a.m., Cinemax Tuesday at 6:30 
a.m.). 
</P>
<P>
 Other four-star films airing this week: 
</P>
<P>
 Unfaithfully Yours (1948 version) Cinemax, Wednesday, 9 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
 America, America AMC, Wednesday, 8 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
 All the President's Men KCOP, Thursday, 2:30 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
 Death in Venice Bravo, Thursday, 7:35 p.m., Friday at midnight and 2 p.m. 
Kevin Thomas 
</P>
