<HEADLINE>
<P>
COFFIN NAILS HAILED: 'CUT HEALTH COSTS' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Smoking may be bad for your health but it aids the economy because it kills 
people before they become a health-care burden, says Canada's largest tobacco 
manufacturer. 
</P>
<P>
 "A person who dies of lung cancer at age 70 will not be hospitalized later 
with another disease," said a study commissioned by Imperial Tobacco touting 
the benefits of early death in smokers on the health-care system. 
</P>
<P>
 " . . . Anti-smoking groups rarely consider the reduction in health costs 
resulting from the premature death of certain smokers; and yet, this 
calculation must be made in order to avoid serious error," said the study, 
written by Montreal economist Jean-Pierre Vidal. 
</P>
<P>
 Vidal's report sparked protests Friday from anti-smokers. 
</P>
<P>
 "The idea that life has no value is incredibly offensive," said David Sweanor, 
senior legal counsel for the Non-Smokers' Rights Assn. lobbying group. "It is 
terribly offensive from a human standpoint. It misses what human life is really 
about." 
</P>
