<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY: SCREENWRITING: CONTEST FOR MINORITIES TO BE HELD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The National Writers Workshop, a nonprofit organization for hopeful 
screenwriters, is holding its fifth annual screenwriting contest for 
minorities. 
</P>
<P>
 American Film Institute graduate Willard Rogers founded the contest in 1990 as 
part of the workshop's Ethnic Minority Screenwriters Development and 
Promotional Program. 
</P>
<P>
 Rogers, 53, head of the organization, established the $500 scholarship to 
discover talent in ethnic communities, which account for only 2.5% of writers 
employed by the motion picture industry. 
</P>
<P>
 Five winners will be chosen. According to Rogers, at least half of the 
previous scholarship winners have been hired by major motion picture studios. 
The entry deadline is Dec. 16. 
</P>
