<HEADLINE>
<P>
ATLANTIC COAST ROUNDUP; FLORIDA STATE HAS NO TROUBLE ON FIELD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Florida State, plagued by problems during the off-season, had no problems in 
its opener Saturday against Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
 Danny Kanell, following in the footsteps of Heisman Trophy winner Charlie 
Ward, passed for 330 yards and four touchdowns as the defending national 
champions crushed the Cavaliers, 41-17, at Tallahassee, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
 The fourth-ranked Seminoles played without seven suspended players, including 
All-American linebacker Derrick Brooks and three offensive linemen who were 
penalized for accepting improper gifts from agents. However, the team did just 
fine without them. 
</P>
<P>
 "The offense started a little slow, but the defense came out there pretty 
pumped up," Kanell said. 
</P>
<P>
 Coach Bobby Bowden said he didn't think the team's off-the-field problems, 
which included the arrest of several players, had any impact on the game. 
</P>
<P>
 "They played good today because they wanted to win and because they were 
defending national champions," said Bowden, who sat on a sideline stool part of 
the game to rest his bad back. 
</P>
<P>
 Kanell, who passed for five touchdowns against Maryland last season when Ward 
was injured, was impressive again in leading the Seminoles to their 17th 
consecutive Atlantic Coast Conference victory. 
</P>
<P>
 The junior passed for three touchdowns in the second quarter -- 16 yards to 
Warrick Dunn, three to Billy Glenn and four to Kez McCorvey. He hit McCorvey 
with another scoring pass, a three-yarder, in the fourth period. 
</P>
<P>
 "I thought he played well," said Ward, who watched from a coaching booth in 
the press box, where he spoke to Kanell on the phone several times during the 
game. 
</P>
<P>
 No. 18 North Carolina 27, Texas Christian 17 -- Jason Stanicek had 244 yards 
of offense in the first half to help the Tar Heels overcome four turnovers and 
a blocked field goal at Chapel Hill, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
 Stanicek passed for 179 yards and rushed for 65 as the Tar Heels built a 
10-point halftime lead. But the Tar Heels, playing without four injured 
starters, nearly gave the game away in the second half. 
</P>
<P>
 Stanicek, who finished with 230 yards passing and 80 rushing, had two passes 
intercepted in the second half. And teammate Curtis Johnson lost a fumble. 
</P>
<P>
 TCU, which has 19 starters back from a team that was 4-7 last season, also 
blocked a 34-yard field-goal attempt early in the fourth quarter to stay within 
24-17. 
</P>
<P>
 But a third-down sack by Oscar Sturgis after the block put TCU out of scoring 
range, and Stanicek engineered a six-minute scoring drive late in the fourth 
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
 No. 24 Clemson 27, Furman 6 -- Emory Smith, brother of Emmitt Smith of the 
Dallas Cowboys, scored two touchdowns and freshman Anthony Downs ran for 89 
yards to lead the Tigers at Clemson, S.C. 
</P>
<P>
 Smith's second-half touchdowns on runs of three and two yards helped Clemson 
overcome a sloppy effort against the NCAA Division I-AA Paladins. 
</P>
<P>
 Clemson outgained Furman, 377 yards to 99, but gave up 205 yards on kickoff 
returns and committed nine penalties for 92 yards. 
</P>
<P>
 It was the first regular-season victory for Clemson Coach Tommy West, who made 
his debut in last season's Peach Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
 Duke 49, Maryland 16 -- Robert Baldwin set a Duke rushing record with 238 
yards and tied a record with four touchdowns at Durham, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
 Baldwin broke the mark of 234 yards set by Randy Cuthbert in 1989 against 
Georgia Tech. 
</P>
<P>
 Before Saturday, Baldwin's best day was 81 yards in 21 carries last year 
against North Carolina State. His four touchdowns -- on runs of three, one, 11 
and 34 yards -- tied Mike Dunn's record set against North Carolina in 1976. 
</P>
