<HEADLINE>
<P>
NO PROOF HEMP PLANTS WERE STOLEN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * Regarding "Hemp's Half Acre" (Aug. 28), I would like to make some comments 
regarding my company. 
</P>
<P>
 The piece was a fairly well-balanced account of this significant and 
historical event involving the potentially premier fiber crop of the next 
century, our company and the state authorities this past summer. 
</P>
<P>
 However, the most disturbing (and predictable) assertion made by Imperial 
County narcotics officers that "local children were . . . stealing plants" is 
without any known proof. To our knowledge there are no police reports or 
complaints to substantiate this sensational claim. 
</P>
<P>
 In regard to the possibility of indictments issued against the participants in 
this experiment, we were told by the officers involved that there would be 
none. To say we are still under investigation by the attorney general's office 
is, to our knowledge, untrue. Our guess is the authorities hope this whole 
incident would just go away, rather than renew interest in legitimate, 
industrial hemp research and production. 
</P>
<P>
 Finally, you omitted the fact that the Hempstead Co. was in fact founded by 
myself, David Martyn and Chris Boucher. 
</P>
<P>
 BRIAN AMBROSE 
</P>
<P>
 Costa Mesa 
</P>
</TEXT>
