<HEADLINE>
<P>
TAX DISCRIMINATION AGAINST THE MARRIED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * It's time we demanded family equality and eliminated the joint income tax 
return. If Richard Katz thinks unmarried couples deserve all the benefits of 
married couples, something has to give. 
</P>
<P>
 Either I want to have my cake and eat it too or people who live together 
should start paying a larger share.  
</P>
<P>
 Those perceived rights these people think they have come at a price. At this 
point, a price that's being picked up by those unfortunate enough to be married 
and file a joint return. To the tune of $3,000 for my family, that's how much 
we would have gotten back had we been allowed to file separately, not including 
what we had to pay. That's $3,000 that will help pay the benefits to the 
unmarried couples who will pocket their individual tax returns.  
</P>
<P>
 I've got news for you people who are cheering this on the sidelines. Don't 
think that I'm the only one aware of this. How long before Mr. Katz puts forth 
a bill to make you pay your fair share? It's probably already written, just 
waiting for all of you to be signed up. Otherwise, it will open the door to a 
massive class action suit against the government, based on discrimination 
against married couples. An open and closed case, I might add. 
</P>
<P>
 RONNIE JAMES 
</P>
<P>
 Glendale 
</P>
</TEXT>
