<HEADLINE>
<P>
RACING ROUNDUP; FOURTH PLACE ALL PHIPPS NEEDS TO CLINCH TITLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RON STAPP 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Dave Phipps highlighted a handful of championship performances at Saugus 
Speedway on Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
 The Simi Valley resident clinched his record seventh track title -- and fourth 
straight in the Grand American Modified division -- with a fourth-place finish 
in the 30-lap main event. 
</P>
<P>
 Robert Rice of Lakewood completed a perfect night by taking the checkered flag 
in the feature race. He also won the six-lap trophy dash and the eight-lap fast 
heat race. 
</P>
<P>
 Phipps, who finished the night 33 points ahead of second-place Dave 
Blankenship of Reseda with one night of racing left this season, joined 
Valencia's John Schultz, who captured the Street Stock championship. 
</P>
<P>
 The final leg of the six-race Sportsman Championship Series also was decided, 
but results were unavailable by press time due to lengthy delays following an 
accident two laps into the 75-lap event involving several cars, including 
series points leader Ron Daniels of San Bernardino and Mark Wilson of 
Bakersfield. 
</P>
<P>
 Daniels entered the race having only to finish within 10 positions of Wilson 
and Pat Mintey Jr. of Quartz Hill, who were tied for second. 
</P>
<P>
 Neither Daniels or Wilson returned to the track once racing restarted. 
</P>
<P>
 Schultz clinched the points championship despite finishing fourth in the final 
25-lap oval main event of the season. In fact, the Valencia resident had 
already wrapped up the title by winning the four-lap trophy dash, which moved 
him 27-points ahead of second-place Kirk Miller of Alta Loma. 
</P>
<P>
 Miller wound up winning the oval main event, pulling away for his sixth 
feature win of the year. 
</P>
<P>
 In other racing action, Sal Rose broke the Sportsman qualifying record with a 
one-lap time of 15.99 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
 Pat Mintey Jr. of Quartz Hill held the previous record (16.06) set on April 2, 
opening night this season. RON STAPP 
</P>
