<HEADLINE>
<P>
FINANCE CHIEF IN BRAZIL QUITS OVER REMARK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Brazil's finance minister has resigned following media reports of a 
conversation in which he admitted slanting economic data to help the 
government-backed presidential candidate. 
</P>
<P>
 President Itamar Franco on Saturday accepted the resignation and said he was 
"shocked and perplexed" by the comments, Globo television reported Saturday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
 Finance Minister Rubens Ricupero made his indiscreet remarks Thursday in what 
he thought was a private chat with a Globo television reporter. But their 
conversation was picked up by network microphones and inadvertently transmitted 
to customers with parabolic antennas. 
</P>
<P>
 "I have no scruples. What is good, we take advantage of. What is bad, we 
hide," Ricupero said according to transcripts of the conversation reprinted 
Saturday by newspapers throughout Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
 Cardoso's popularity has risen steadily since May, in part because many 
Brazilians credit him with bringing inflation under control. 
</P>
<P>
 The latest poll shows Cardoso with the support of 45% of the electorate, 
well-ahead of leftist Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva's 23%, a month ahead of Oct. 3 
elections. 
</P>
