<HEADLINE>
<P>
READER APPRECIATES A WRITER'S EFFORTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 I appreciated the story headlined "Teamsters Target Sam's Club in Fullerton" 
(Aug. 8). 
</P>
<P>
 Here's a news story that actually adheres to the old 
who-what-when-where-and-how rule of journalism. The lead paragraph actually 
summarizes the story; the subsequent paragraphs are in descending order of 
importance. It's reassuring to see a news story written in the traditional 
manner. It actually imparts information clearly and concisely. What a change 
from the all-too-frequent "cutesy" leads and filler paragraphs that divert 
readers' attention from the facts. 
</P>
<P>
 DOTTIE GROSSMAN 
</P>
<P>
 Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
